textDisplay:
So first of all, thank you to Enes for an, as ever, very professional tour. There are aspects of this interior which I like very much, despite a somewhat awkward layout but I think that any discussion of 432 Park Avenue isn't really complete without addressing some of the problems of the building itself.

The residents are currently suing the developers over the more than 1,500 faults in the building. They cite stuck elevators, flooding, electrical explosions and noise caused by building sway as just some of the problems. They are reportedly seeking $125m plus punitive damages. I'm not sure about the rest of this comment section but I certainly wouldn't be in a hurry to move into a building with those sorts of issues.
textOriginal:

The residents are currently suing the developers over the more than 1,500 faults in the building. textDisplay: I know many people didn´t like it, because they say it is too simple, but I loved it, I suppose everything is about personal taste. Many houses presented here I don´t like because they are too exaggerated, I prefer something more simple and minimalist, besides this kind of design allows you to go wild with the decorations, I can imagine filling it with plants and paintings. On the other hand, in a house or apartment too ornate   you have to be more careful with the decoration, because it can look overwhelming. Besides, I think we all know the value of this apartment depends a lot on its location. New York is an expensive city, where even a small apartment with one bedroom and one bathroom can look overpriced if you compare it with apartments in a different place. If you want to live in the center of a big important city, you have to pay for it...

textDisplay: 0:58 That's a morally ambiguous drone shot of the skyscraper. At what distance would you need consent from the residents to video their living rooms and bedrooms like that? What if the drone were half as far away and you could see inside the rooms? If you're on the 70something floor of a high-rise you are not expecting cameras to be peeking into your windows and therefore you're not going to hang curtains. And predictably, half the windows have no curtains or other visual barriers for that reason: because at that height you have a reasonable expectation of privacy. You could be walking around naked or doing things with your significant other and then suddenly a drone with a camera shows up.

textDisplay:
I've been totally stunned by all the NYC residences you've shown but I'm pretty conflicted about this one. What I do like about it, I love - the bathrooms and the kitchen. The blue tonetta tuff stone in the bathrooms is exquisite and the fixtures and details are perfect. Clean, spacious, elegant. The kitchen is also a wonderful mix of upscale comfort and NYC commercial restaurant vibe. I love the hand hammered aluminium, the oversized pantry, the large stove/oven fixture. But for me, that's all the good there is.

The rest of the home, I wouldn't call it "cold" because it certainly has warm tones but I would call it tepid, tight, empty, unfinished and I hate to say it but... Soulless really. It looks more like a commercial space than a home. With the bedrooms being the worst of it. The salon is also pretty terrible. There's nothing about it that would make me want to spend any time there. It also seems as though (bathrooms being the exception) that the house was designed for smaller humans no bigger than 5'7" 160lbs. Everything is tight and narrow. Like the space behind the bar in the salon. If you opened a drawer, you'd barely have enough room to stand behind it. The hallway that leaves the main salon and accesses the bedrooms, laundry etc, it's so narrow and unfinished that it frankly looks like the hallway in a seedy Asian "massage parlor." The entire house and it's sliding doors, wood fixtures etc - looks almost flimsy. As if anything would snap or crack with the slightest of mishap.

At the end of the video when night came, it did improve the vibe quite a bit and I can see that the residence really shines at night. Regardless, to me it does not justify the price tag. The last two NYC residences I watched that you toured, one at $39 million, one at just below $50 million I think, I'd have chosen those. Even if I had seen them without the price tags, I'd never have thought that this one would be about THREE times the price of those.

If I was to live here, the bathrooms and kitchen would certainly stay as is but the rest of the home would have to be ripped down and redone from scratch to make it feel like a home instead of empty, commercial office space for rent.

Aside from my critique of the residence, once again a great tour by Enes and Mikey! 👌🏻🍻💯

textDisplay: We have the exact same taps in our bathroom they're around $300. In this apartment however they've been installed upside down lol (the temperature control handle is supposed to be face down). In fact the finishing of this house uses a lot of very cheap and affordable materials (like we can afford as first home owners in Japan)... I also noticed that the power fixtures in the shelves had not been cut and installed flush to size - some obvious gaps are visible in the fitting... I'd expect everything to be custom and meticulously hand made (crafted, not factory made) for this price, it's insane. For sure all the cost is in the location, but then again, many people in New York do not like this Tower as it is too tall and ugly. How many people already have apartments in this tower? You can hardly call this property unique or exclusive in terms of location if another hundred people live at the same address. Best room in the house was the master bathroom with the two vertical stone slabs and hinoki wood slat interior, basically the only room where the design was at the level you'd expect for this price.

textDisplay: Amazingly, an American couple obsessed with Asian art had Sugimoto design this. Centuries ago this was the case w/ the European aristocracy and they spent vast sums of wealth on lacquered furniture and trinkets from the Orient until they figured out the closely-guarded secret to making them: turpentine. I love this space because it makes ZERO compromises. They likely let Sugimoto run wild in the tea room w/ Feng shui then said "Do the entire place." To the haters: Shut your child mouths. This is old Japanese tradition and the only luxury condo I see driven by a cultural tradition rather than contemporary modernity. In that regard, it's a jewel. Is it for everyone? Nothing is for everyone so discuss it in its own context. Who gives a damn what you would or wouldn't' do w/ $135m? This would be a gas chamber to you anyway without a flatscreen TV. What piece of modern art on the wall could compete w/ the dining room floor made from 1000 yr old cedar from Yakushima island, totally illegal to get now, they had to harvest it from pre-ban storage. You point down to your friend and say "See those swirls... that's from centuries of winds ripping Yakushima island swaying those trees." So, soooooo Japanese. Those old stones in the bathroom? Taken from an abandoned train station in Kyoto, crews of Japanese craftsmen were flown in to set them properly, the whole condo took four years of back-and-forth to Japan. I note the sell of this place is not contingent upon maintaining it as-is. Someone could go in and gut this place and turn it into some Jewish financier or Saudi billionaire's taste or J-Lo's or whoever's - it would be a crying shame though. You go to their dinner parties and it's "There's our new Basquiat, it's about racism... see, he doodled out a police car and he even wrote "racism."" They come to yours - there's my 10-ft long Komatsu stone - a symbol of power during the Edo Period. It's just so elemental. Leave your $2000 Ferragamo heels at the door, you're in Japan now.

textDisplay:
With everything I’ve read about that building that apartment will never sell. That building is supposedly a house of horrors that swings wildly when it’s windy and has severe water & sewage problems. Another bad thing is residents have to pay an exorbitant amount of money a year for the restaurant “club” (it’s like 10 times more than what was originally agreed for residents that already live there). Also the elevators are literally out of service more than they work so you’re stuck walking up countless steps to get up and down. People that bought places high up the building hated it so much they sold them for massive losses (tens of millions of dollars). The reason it’s so bad is because the building is way too narrow for how high it is so it sways too much and messes up the sewage & elevators etc.
Edit: in parts of this video when the light is right you can see parts of the plaster that’s become wavy. I can’t imagine how much money the people that built/own that building are losing. They shouldn’t have made it so tall and should’ve known how bad the building would sway. You can read peoples’ experiences being in that building when it’s storming outside and it’s rocking back & forth.

textDisplay:
I am a born and bred New Yorker from the upper east side. Ask any New Yorker: this building is an eyesore. We call it the pencil building. It’s a tall, skinny, lego building, lacking any beauty or architectural style. It casts a long and miserable shadow over one of the most beloved treasures of our city: Central Park.

People (mostly investors who contribute nothing to the vibrancy and community) who purchase apartments here just want to show that they can afford the big ticket price (we have lots of those - this being the worst). It’s so tall, it sways (what fun!) and also the Times just ran an article on how poorly this was built.

If you want to showcase beautiful, high end buildings in NYC, please skip this ugly disaster - it’s tourist fodder.

textDisplay: Tomb chic I guess and as cold as sashimi on a plate. The bedroom looks cramped and narrow. The parlor looks as inviting as an avant-garde sterile museum. I can even see a robot dressed in kabuki theater garb serving tea which becomes an eccentric owner’s bestie. The views are amazing but what is with the ‘ plaster ‘ division support beams all over the place. And I hear the building has problems galore. Can you imagine not being able to take an elevator up because the wind is too strong? I wonder when this sinks and becomes the east coast version of the sinking building in San Fran whether they will literally meet in the middle. Japanese architecture should be about serenity and tranquility and gardens with indoor outdoor living. This design reflects agoraphobic imprisonment with emotionless stares out the window.
